The paper deals with piecewise testable languages, which are a subclass of regular languages. This falls under the category of formal languages (cs.FL). The paper presents an algorithm for computing the canonical representative of the $\sim_k$-class of a given word, which involves manipulating subwords of the input word. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of data structures (cs.DS) and computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also discusses the computation of shortlex normal forms, which involves ordering words lexicographically, indicating a possible connection to information theory (cs.IT) and logic in computer science (cs.LO).
